Share this...FacebookTwitterFrom 1993 to 2018, the satellite altimetry sea level changes reveal both positive and negative accelerations, align with oscillatory patterns, and are dominated by internal variability (e.g., PDO, ENSO). The ‚Äúforced acceleration pattern‚Äù assumed to be associated with anthropogenic global warming ‚Äúhas not emerged‚Äù.

Image Source: Hamlington et al., 2020
Negative or negligible sea level accelerations both in recent years and in the long-term record.
For years scientists have been trying to detect an anthropogenic influence in sea level changes globe as manifested by an acceleration that rises out of the range of natural variability.
While there was an acceleration in sea level rise trends from 1993 to 2003, since 2004 negative accelerations (-0.08 mm/year¬≤) have emerged in the global satellite record (Chen et al., 2014; Dean and Houston, 2013).

Image Source: Chen et al., 2014

Image Source: Dean and Houston, 2013
For the long-term trend, when cleared of multi-decadal oscillations, ‚Äúthere is no sign of acceleration‚Äù in sea level changes across the globe.
In the locations where the tide gauge record do evince acceleration, they are still ‚Äúremarkably close to zero‚Äù (Boretti, 2020).

Image Source: Boretti, 2020
An anthropogenic fingerprint in post-1993 sea level changes still ‚Äútoo small‚Äù to be detected


