Climate change or climate crisis? To really engage people, the media should talk about¬†solutionsMay 30, 2019 10.33pm AESTDimitrinka Atanasova Lecturer in Linguistics, Lancaster UniversityKjersti Fl√∏ttum Professor of Linguistics, University of BergenDays after the British parliament¬†declared¬†a ‚Äúclimate emergency‚Äù, The Guardian¬†announced¬†that it would start using ‚Äústronger‚Äù language to discuss the environment. Its updated style guide states that ‚Äúclimate change‚Äù no longer accurately reflects the seriousness of the situation and journalists are advised to use ‚Äúclimate emergency‚Äù, ‚Äúclimate crisis‚Äù or ‚Äúclimate breakdown‚Äù instead.‚Ä¶But the ‚Äústrong‚Äù language of ‚Äúbreakdown‚Äù, ‚Äúcrisis‚Äù, ‚Äúemergency‚Äù and ‚Äúwar‚Äù may have unintended consequences.‚Ä¶Fear appeals might also have¬†the opposite effect¬†to what is intended, causing indifference, apathy and feelings of powerlessness. When people see a problem as¬†too big, they might stop believing that anything can be done to solve it. If fear is to motivate people, then studies suggest that¬†a solution must also be presented¬†to focus minds on action.‚Ä¶Informing people about wars, crises and emergencies is an important part of the media‚Äôs role, but we may have reached ‚Äúpeak negativity‚Äù, where the news is so full of¬†serious crises¬†that people are¬†increasingly avoiding it. They are left feeling disengaged, demotivated and depressed about the state of the world and their role in it.Constructive journalism¬†should take a solution-focused approach that covers problems with the appropriate seriousness, but also answers the inevitable ‚Äúwhat now?‚Äù, by describing how similar problems have been addressed elsewhere in the world. Awareness of climate change is¬†high and growing, but the¬†potential solutions need more attention.‚Ä¶Read more: https://theconversation.com/climate-change-or-climate-crisis-to-really-engage-people-the-media-should-talk-about-solutions-118004
