The suit focuses on Exxon‚Äôs use of an internal ‚Äúproxy‚Äù price for global warming regulations, which was lower than prices put forward in reports to investors and the public. Exxon said it‚Äôs been internally pricing carbon dioxide emissions since 2007. Tillerson was the CEO during that time.
The ploy ‚Äúin effect erected a Potemkin village to create the illusion that it had fully considered the risks of future climate change regulation,‚Äù the lawsuit stated. New York‚Äôs initial probe stems from research conducted by Inside Climate News, which reported in 2015 that the company downplays whatever role it contributes to man-made global warming.
Barbara Underwood, the state‚Äôs former interim attorney general, brought the lawsuit under the Martin Act, a state law giving the state broad authority to prosecute securities fraud. The suit demands Exxon turn over any profits the company made through the alleged fraud and make restitution to investors.
